escription
This project is the first phase of the HBnB Evolution application. The objective is to design the application's
architecture and business logic using UML diagrams before implementation.
Project Overview:
HBnB Evolution is a multi-tier accommodation marketplace application managing users, places, reviews, and
amenities.


The design follows a three-layer architecture:
Presentation Layer:
 Manages public REST endpoints, parses user requests, and returns serialized HTTP
status payloads.
Business Logic Layer:
 Coordinates domain structures and runs state verification rules.
Persistence Layer:
 Abstracts raw storage access using transactional databases

Design Choices and Rationale
The Facade Pattern Integration: The Presentation Layer interfaces exclusively with a unified Facade
class sitting inside the Business Logic Layer. This decouples API routing handlers from internal subsystem
changes, hides object instantiation complexities, and ensures core validation rules remain insulated.
Decoupled CRUD Operations: Communication between the Business Logic and Persistence Layers
relies entirely on standardized CRUD repository abstractions. This isolates database storage routines,
allowing back-end database changes to occur with zero modifications to the core business logic models.

API Interaction Flow
Runtime Layer Orchestration
To process API calls seamlessly without tight component coupling, requests traverse through clear system
boundaries following this sequential lifecycle:
Client → Sends parameters to a public routing endpoint in the PresentationLayer (API) .
API Controller → Maps variables, sanitizes inputs, and calls the unified Facade .
Facade Interface → Forwards parameters to validate constraints inside the BusinessLogicLayer .
Domain Entities → Execute core business logic and delegate state mutations to the
PersistenceLayer .
Repository Engine → Commits data changes safely to long-term storage ( Database ).

Objectives
Design the system architecture using UML.
Model the application's business entities and their relationships.
Illustrate interactions between application layers.
Provide documentation to guide future implementation.
